title: Grateful Dead Live at Cal Expo on 1991-08-14
description: Touch Of Gray, Little Red Rooster, Loser, Black Throated Wind, Row Jimmy, Cassidy, Don't Ease Me In Cold Rain & Snow, Box Of Rain, Looks Like Rain, Crazy Fingers-> Estimated Prophet-> Supplication Jam-> Uncle John's Band-> Drums-> Jam-> The Other One-> Walkin' Blues-> Around & Around, E: Knockin' On Heaven's Door

reviews.review_text: Great 2nd set Not familiar with 1st set. Very consistent killer energy throughout the 2nd "Rain" set.  My fav set of the strong Expo-Shoreline run. Great sounding SBD.  The other "SBD" is actually a really nice sounding audience recording.  My favorite Cold Rain of all time (post a date if you prefer another!).  Box of Rain bursts with energy - another all time great performance.  Usually dislike the cheesiness of Looks Like Rain, but they nail this one.  Sparkling Crazy Fingers with great piano work and flawless playing. Thundering Phil 'kaboom' to open a solid Other One.  Blah blah blah - kick back and listen for yourself - the boys are ON and in a great zone.  Wore out my tape over past 10+ years, glad to get a new copy! Enjoy, you've found a gem.
yea pretty good sound.. it is not barton hall sound but it is still worth it

greatful drench My wife and I were at this show and I remember getting poured on - in the spirit of the moment we got three rain songs in a row and in 25 years of dead shows that was a first for me...

Take care, friends
Robert Sommers

very cool just when you think you've heard it all...
   I was/am very familiar with the following night of the 16th for the scarlet>victom>fire hornsby rich piano, this date has something too. listen to the acordian sound on cold rain, box of rain, very cool, 
  great mix, you can hear bobby just fine, something i struggle with at times in later years, jerry's voice is strong for 90s standards and the drums are as on as they ever were post 77.

Something Good Comes From Sacramento It is unimaginable that Sac could get this much rain in the summer. Usually, it is bone dry with temps in the 100's. Yet the city does get the occasional thunderbumper which drifts in from Mexico as the tail end of a Hurricane.

Surely did not dampen the hearts of those on stage, nor those in the crowd. They don't seem too bummed ~ after all, many of them toured with the GD and would already be quite well-acclimated to the summer thunder storms that happen like clockwork all over the rest of the States.

And what is it about high humidity and precipitation that makes PA systems seem to come alive? This is an exceedingly phat and ritch mix. Even your old fave Don't Ease sounds great. Playing and singing doesn't suck, either!

Plus, this is a nicely re-mastered and well-transfered recording. Thank you, Daryl Hinko.

Vince is too all over it in Cold Rain and his hectic racing back and forth to change dynamics doesn't set well with Bruce's accordian. It fairly rocks, though. Then Phil steps to the plate and delivers Box of Rain, a song so good that anyone can sing it. Speaking of Phil, his bass playing is so perfectly captured and recorded in his show, you can almost just focus on nothing else and still receive the full onslaught of the ensemble.
Which is what I enjoy about Looks Like Rain. It's slower and more understated than most, but because of it's wide-opened, tree-lined avenues the bass can verily roar roughshod and set the scene for Jerry to insert his tortured fire bough's. From that effect he slides into his reedy horn thing then floats between wispy splashes of the torch in the rain. Absolutely gorgeous! It is the appearance of ancient Greek gods falling down, evaporating and rising up into...

Crazy Fingers. This is an excellent version and Phil is phreaking phanatical! When Jerry drops into his solo it ejects a giant tear from the great cloud of weight hanging the sky that day.
This song is so heartfelt, I want to make a loop of it and listen to it 7 times in a row. Bruce and Jerry tussle with each other in the outro. Spectacular! You must play this LOUD.

Out of it they pause and go into Estimated. The lead-in is colored sveltely with Bruce and Vince spinning glorious chords and them coupled with Jerry's ominous shadings, 'tis mystical. Phil is just flat-out out-of-hand! Insane! These two songs ~ Fingers and Estimated are...immaculate... exquisite.

A marvelous freeform piano/sax jam erupts twixt all seven, Jerry tossing in tiny pebbles of logic to ripple the air. Intoxicating. Just when you thought is was safe to go back into the sky, out pours Supplication jousting its way into Unca John. Sounds like Jerry knocks Bobby out of the saddle, for, after the supersonic excursion which proceeded it poses a rather ackward and disharmonious transition yet Unca John is presented with such verve and confidence that it carries the flag. Halfway through UJB the recording cuts into what sounds like an AUD Patch, and then it streamlines back into the SBD for drumz. Drumz and space is rather predictable. If you can appreciate it, "space" can be comforting. This version sounds very similar to many of 1991, but suddenly, why does this space comfort me? -- 'Cause it's predictable. Does that make sense?

Said another way, this particular night's space is easy to entreat. To lure you into it's goof, it paints this mock intensely gloomy portrait then spins on a dime and dosey-doze its way right into the Other One. 

Wharf and Around and Heaven's Door are pedestrian, but the sound on this recording is so vibrant that it more than compensates. And you're right at the gate. But be forewarned: There are some pestilent screeches on the recording near the mid peak.

This concert rates a 10.

Thank you for posting this show I enjoyed it thoroughly.

RWS

Cal Expo rocks Yes 3 consecutive rain songs but after listening I heard Bruce tuning between songs playing "Raindrops keep falling on my head" The boys always played and sounded good @ Expo, It was like a home game for them they could sleep in their own beds each night. What was a given was that Drums were going to shine. They would put 2 speaker towers at the top back of the bleachers and literally get the sound spinning in a circle Mickey had some of the best sessions on "The Beam" that I had ever heard. This show was fun and it plays that way also.

Not bad... ...but still, I'm glad I didn't accept that girl's invitation in Colorado.

 This was, I think, the best show of the three-night run, and I just don't find it all that good. "Supplication jam" notwithstanding, there's really nothing too ear-catching here. Welnick & Hornsby's keyboards compete with each other to drown out everyone else. 

Compared to traveling to a stinking desert with a beautiful but hungry-vibed hippie girl with tickets to a trio of crappy to lackluster Dead shows, I'm glad I went from Denver back home to Eugene to look fruitlessly for a job and fight with my roommates. These shows do not sound like the stuff legends are made of.

excellent sound quality but performance is spotty.

Rooster, Loser, BTWind, Row Jimmy are excellent versions, and 2nd half of Estimated, Drums/Space are jamming, but otherwise there's not much to show for their efforts.

Warning, some loud momentary electronic static during Heaven's Door.
rain hey on this night it had not rained in 127 days and it poured right before 2nd set i loved this night it was so much fun i hear more fussin'  on this sight than at anytime on the tour

Respectfully disagree I was at this show so I'm maybe biased but I think there is some ear catching stuff here. Jerry is playing off the extra keys to sprinkle sweet notes all over the place in this show and everyone is on. Rain songs then the jam.. Nice solid flow all from and through the drumspace into the comfort of the familiar backend... Jeez what more do you want from 1991?

GD Cal Expo 8-14-1991 Incredible weather, people, and band.
Run with the whole show

Cal Expo These shows kicked off a great week of 6 shows in 7 days with Shoreline following. Cal Expo was bearable with the weather actually cooperating. The downpour during set break was totally refreshing and then they threw the rain trilogy at us to start 2nd set. Lots of fun being had. My memory of the day was the sun popping out and the whole place dancing and singing Uncle John's Band together as one. Truly a day to remember...
